00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:06.300
It shows up a lot.

00:03:06.300 --> 00:03:08.995
All right, so this,
as we went through,

00:03:08.995 --> 00:03:10.620
and it's basically
just saying that I'm

00:03:10.620 --> 00:03:12.270
going to take the
covariant derivative

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:15.037
of the tangent vector u
and contract it with u.

00:03:15.037 --> 00:03:16.620
OK, and there's a
couple of other ways

00:03:16.620 --> 00:03:18.412
of writing this which
I've written out here

00:03:18.412 --> 00:03:19.615
in just sort of notation.

00:03:19.615 --> 00:03:21.490
But if you expand it
out, it looks like this.

00:03:21.490 --> 00:03:24.300
So what you're saying
is that the vector

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:28.050
u, the four-vector components
u, are parameterized

00:03:28.050 --> 00:03:30.383
by some quantity which if
it's a time-like trajectory,

00:03:30.383 --> 00:03:31.800
you can think of
it as essentially

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:35.317
the proper time as you
move along that trajectory.

00:03:35.317 --> 00:03:36.900
This is just describing
how this thing

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:40.260
behaves as a function
of that parameter, OK.

00:03:40.260 --> 00:03:42.120
So we're going to do
some more with that.

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:45.570
To begin with, there's
a couple of cool results

00:03:45.570 --> 00:03:46.890
that we can derive.

00:03:46.890 --> 00:03:48.060
So there's a nice side note.

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:51.200
We can rewrite this
in terms of momentum.

00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:03.680
So if you imagine, let's
focus on the version

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:08.870
where I'm doing it
per units proper time.

00:04:08.870 --> 00:04:18.610
And I'm going to take advantage
of the fact that for a body

00:04:18.610 --> 00:04:25.640
moving on a
time-like trajectory,

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:34.720
so a body with a rest mass
m, I just take this equation,

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:37.870
and basically, you
multiply by m twice,

00:04:37.870 --> 00:04:45.580
and it very clearly turns into
something that is pretty much

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:50.530
exactly the same, but I just
replace my u's with p's.

00:04:50.530 --> 00:04:52.840
Two comments I want
to make about this.

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:55.975
So first, and you know what,
let me actually expand this out.

00:04:55.975 --> 00:04:57.100
I mean, it's quite obvious.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:00.505
Why don't we write it in
terms of the components

00:05:00.505 --> 00:05:01.630
in the Christoffel symbols.

00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:15.730
OK, so I'm going to
write it like this.

00:05:15.730 --> 00:05:17.070
Let's do the following, OK.

00:05:17.070 --> 00:05:20.540
Recall that if I have-- so
this trajectory, assuming, when

00:05:20.540 --> 00:05:22.290
you write like this,
your parameter lambda

00:05:22.290 --> 00:05:24.180
is called an affine parameter.

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:26.940
And that is a parameter
such that the right hand

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:29.250
side of [INAUDIBLE]
equation is 0 on a free fall

00:05:29.250 --> 00:05:30.330
trajectory, OK.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.370
If it's something that's
proportional to you,

00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:33.810
it is a valid
parameter, but it's

00:05:33.810 --> 00:05:37.650
one that's sort of been
defined in a bad way.

00:05:37.650 --> 00:05:40.020
One thing we showed
last time is that I

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:43.208
can shift lambda
by any constant,

00:05:43.208 --> 00:05:44.250
OK, with the right units.

00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:45.958
That essentially
amounts to just changing

00:05:45.958 --> 00:05:47.250
the origin of my clock.

00:05:47.250 --> 00:05:51.990
And I can multiply it by any
scalar, which essentially

00:05:51.990 --> 00:05:54.780
amounts to changing the units
in which I am measuring time.

00:05:54.780 --> 00:05:56.880
And it's still a good
affine parameter.

00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:59.340
So here's an example
of an affine parameter

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:00.270
that I could use.

00:06:08.410 --> 00:06:12.730
Suppose that I defined
this such that an interval

00:06:12.730 --> 00:06:16.270
of affine parameter delta
lambda is an interval

00:06:16.270 --> 00:06:18.900
of delta tau divided by m.

00:06:25.340 --> 00:06:33.140
If I do this, well,
then, p alpha is just d--

00:06:33.140 --> 00:06:36.968
so remember this is
now going to be--

00:06:36.968 --> 00:06:38.010
let's write it like this.

00:06:38.010 --> 00:06:40.460
So this is my original
definition of this thing.

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:46.172
This then becomes
dx alpha d lambda.

00:06:46.172 --> 00:06:48.380
So this is a way of choosing
an affine parameter such

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:52.490
that I'm essentially writing
my tangent along the world line

00:06:52.490 --> 00:06:55.460
as the momentum rather than
something like the four

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:57.027
velocity, OK?

00:06:57.027 --> 00:06:58.610
But there's something
cool about this,

00:06:58.610 --> 00:07:00.800
so let's now go
and just write what

00:07:00.800 --> 00:07:04.156
my geodesy equation turns into.

00:07:04.156 --> 00:07:05.670
It's basically exactly the same.

00:07:05.670 --> 00:07:09.380
It's just that I'm going to
absorb the m on the first term.

00:07:13.413 --> 00:07:15.830
Basically, it's exactly the
same geodesy equation as I had

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:18.755
before, but with
u's promoted to p's.

00:07:18.755 --> 00:07:22.040
What's kind of
cool about this is

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:28.910
you can take a limit
in which m goes

00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:35.540
to zero as long as your
interval of proper time

00:07:35.540 --> 00:07:51.840
goes to zero at a rate such
that delta t over m is constant.

00:07:55.070 --> 00:07:57.790
So what this allows us to
do is just conceptually

00:07:57.790 --> 00:07:59.740
reformulate the
geodesy equation,

00:07:59.740 --> 00:08:02.050
so that it's perfectly
well behaved.

00:08:02.050 --> 00:08:04.870
Not just for time
like trajectories,

00:08:04.870 --> 00:08:09.358
but for null or light
like trajectories.

00:08:28.810 --> 00:08:30.690
OK, so that's very
important for us.

00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:35.090
A lot of the most important
tests of general relativity

00:08:35.090 --> 00:08:37.429
actually come down to looking
at the behavior of light

00:08:37.429 --> 00:08:40.309
as it moves in some kind
of a curved space time.

00:08:40.309 --> 00:08:42.943
And the geodesy
equation, if you sort of

00:08:42.943 --> 00:08:45.110
interpret the way we thought
about it before, you're

00:08:45.110 --> 00:08:47.798
kind of like, well, let's
go back, and suppose I'm

00:08:47.798 --> 00:08:49.090
running it sort of in this one.

00:08:49.090 --> 00:08:52.020
And I'm thinking of my
lambda as proper time.

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:53.750
An interval with
proper time is not

00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:57.130
defined along a light
like trajectory, OK?

00:08:57.130 --> 00:08:59.430
So that just kind of makes
it clear that that's fine.

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:00.805
What we're going
to do when we're

00:09:00.805 --> 00:09:02.390
talking about a
light like trajectory

00:09:02.390 --> 00:09:05.180
is we're just going to find
the parameter along the world

00:09:05.180 --> 00:09:08.930
line, such that the tangent
vector is the momentum

00:09:08.930 --> 00:09:09.950
along that world line.

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:11.450
Mass doesn't even make sense.

00:09:11.450 --> 00:09:16.340
So the p that goes into
this-- so when I do this,

00:09:16.340 --> 00:09:22.130
this is going to be a p,
such that p alpha p alpha

00:09:22.130 --> 00:09:23.180
equals minus m squared.

00:09:23.180 --> 00:09:25.550
We still have that
rule that it's always

00:09:25.550 --> 00:09:29.450
going to be minus m squared,
which is zero in this case.

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:36.200
So this gives us
a tool that we can

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:38.990
use to study the
motion of light as it

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:40.340
reacts to gravity, for example.

00:09:46.840 --> 00:09:51.100
OK, we'll switch
gears, so I want

00:09:51.100 --> 00:09:55.840
to do one other trick based on
this momentum form of things.

00:09:55.840 --> 00:09:59.322
So I can rewrite the
geodesy equation as follows,

00:09:59.322 --> 00:10:01.030
and it's going to
start out where it just

00:10:01.030 --> 00:10:04.435
looks like I'm essentially doing
what we call index gymnastics.

00:10:04.435 --> 00:10:06.310
I'm just sort of moving
a few indices around.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:28.770
So let's write this as p
alpha, and what I'm going to do

00:10:28.770 --> 00:10:30.270
is contract it on this.

00:10:33.138 --> 00:10:34.680
I'm putting the
index and my momentum

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:36.302
in the downstairs position now.

00:10:36.302 --> 00:10:38.260
First of all, you should
stop and ask yourself,

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:41.220
am I allowed to do that?

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:43.530
If I do that, do I not
generate some additional term

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:45.665
that should then be moved
to the right hand side?

00:10:45.665 --> 00:10:47.040
Well, think about
what I'm doing.

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:53.432
If I am lowering an index, that
essentially means that I am--

00:10:53.432 --> 00:10:54.390
let's do the following.

00:10:54.390 --> 00:10:56.140
Let's change this to
a gamma for a second.

00:11:00.350 --> 00:11:02.590
What I have done here
is I have essentially

00:11:02.590 --> 00:11:09.440
taken the equation
I wrote over there,

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:15.710
and I had hit it with
g beta gamma, OK?

00:11:15.710 --> 00:11:17.900
I can always multiply
by those things.

00:11:17.900 --> 00:11:21.380
The covariant derivative
of the metric is zero.

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:24.200
Because the covariant derivative
of the metric is zero,

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:25.670
it commutes with
that derivative,

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:28.266
so I can just walk it inside
the derivative operator.

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:45.793
So I wanted to go through
that just a little

00:11:45.793 --> 00:11:47.377
bit carefully, because
that's actually

00:11:47.377 --> 00:11:49.090
a trick that once
you've seen it once,

00:11:49.090 --> 00:11:50.260
I want you to know it well.

00:11:50.260 --> 00:11:52.180
Because I'm just going to
do it many, many times as we

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:52.810
move forward.

00:11:52.810 --> 00:11:53.620
There's going to be
a bunch of times,

00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:54.640
where I'm taking the partial--

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:56.400
it's going to be the covariant
derivative is something.

00:11:56.400 --> 00:11:58.900
I know it's going be raising
indices willy nilly on whatever

00:11:58.900 --> 00:11:59.670
it's operating on.

00:11:59.670 --> 00:12:01.087
But I'm taking it
down to the fact

00:12:01.087 --> 00:12:04.090
that I'm effectively moving a
metric inside and outside here.

00:12:08.470 --> 00:12:14.160
All right, so let's take
that for the geodesy equation

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:16.320
and expand it out.

00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:28.435
So I end up with mdp beta d
tau, so I'm here using the fact

00:12:28.435 --> 00:12:30.060
that the p alpha
that's on the outside,

00:12:30.060 --> 00:12:32.190
I'm writing that as mu alpha.

00:12:32.190 --> 00:12:34.920
And I'm using that to
convert the derivative I get,

00:12:34.920 --> 00:12:37.500
expanding that
into a d by d tau.

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:39.180
And then I get a
term that basically

00:12:39.180 --> 00:12:42.195
corrects the downstairs index.

00:12:49.598 --> 00:12:52.140
Because it's a downstairs index,
it enters with a minus sign.

00:12:54.292 --> 00:12:56.750
Let's move this to the other
side, and what I'm going to do

00:12:56.750 --> 00:13:01.270
is make all the indices be
in the downstairs position.

00:13:01.270 --> 00:13:02.482
Let's see.

00:13:02.482 --> 00:13:03.190
Hang on a second.

00:13:03.190 --> 00:13:04.130
Did I do this right?

00:13:04.130 --> 00:13:04.390
Sorry.

00:13:04.390 --> 00:13:05.890
Yeah, I'm going
make all the indices

00:13:05.890 --> 00:13:09.377
in the downstairs position
on this capital gamma,

00:13:09.377 --> 00:13:10.960
so I'm going to write
this as follows.

00:13:24.850 --> 00:13:27.390
OK, so I chose to
write it this way

00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:28.800
as you'll see in just a moment.

00:13:28.800 --> 00:13:34.440
Because this is now symmetric
on exchange of alpha and gamma.

00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:40.320
Let's expand that
Christoffel symbol,

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:46.170
so I'm going to have one term
beta derivative alpha gamma.

00:14:04.980 --> 00:14:05.980
We'll put this up above.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.203
OK, so take a look at that
last line of that expression.

00:14:23.070 --> 00:14:27.020
So as written here,
I've got a term

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:30.770
that is symmetric on
exchange of alpha and gamma.

00:14:30.770 --> 00:14:33.110
But inside my parentheses,
bearing in mind

00:14:33.110 --> 00:14:35.450
that my metric is itself
a symmetric object,

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:38.210
I've got two terms,
this one and this one,

00:14:38.210 --> 00:14:41.000
where if I exchange alpha and
gamma, I get a minus sign.

00:15:06.300 --> 00:15:10.550
So I got a symmetric
contracted with anti-symmetric.

00:15:10.550 --> 00:15:18.050
Therefore, I can
simplify this whole thing

00:15:18.050 --> 00:15:20.990
to something that
only involves--

00:15:20.990 --> 00:15:23.540
the only derivative
I need to compute

00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:29.525
is one partial
derivative of the metric.

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:44.393
Now that's nice, but
if you think about it,

00:15:44.393 --> 00:15:46.060
it might even be nicer
than you realize.

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:58.150
Suppose you're working in
some coordinate system, such

00:15:58.150 --> 00:16:01.130
that for a particular
derivative, for a particular,

00:16:01.130 --> 00:16:03.070
let's say, it's the
derivative with respect

00:16:03.070 --> 00:16:06.063
to your time coordinate.

00:16:06.063 --> 00:16:07.230
Suppose the metric vanishes.

00:16:29.490 --> 00:16:32.190
Suppose that equals zero
for some coordinate.

00:16:32.190 --> 00:16:35.745
Then you've just learned
that a particular component

00:16:35.745 --> 00:16:38.370
of the four momentum, component
of the downstairs four momentum

00:16:38.370 --> 00:16:43.591
mind you, that is a constant of
the motion along the worldwide.

00:17:11.109 --> 00:17:12.790
I sort of said in
words a few things

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:14.290
about this a couple
lectures ago when we were

00:17:14.290 --> 00:17:15.540
talking about Killing vectors.

00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:17.260
I'm going to actually tie this
to that discussion in just

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:18.170
a moment.

00:17:18.170 --> 00:17:20.140
This is often operationally
the simplest way

00:17:20.140 --> 00:17:22.790
to deduce that you, in fact,
have a constant motion,

