We're going to essentially
put together-- we're

00:37:01.377 --> 00:37:03.000
going to take all
the last ingredients

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:04.500
and develop the
field equations that

00:37:04.500 --> 00:37:06.455
describe relativistic gravity.

00:37:06.455 --> 00:37:07.830
The first thing
we're going to do

00:37:07.830 --> 00:37:10.530
is solve this in a
particular limit that

00:37:10.530 --> 00:37:13.590
describes a body that
is weakly gravitating.

00:37:13.590 --> 00:37:17.400
This will emerge
from this with phi

00:37:17.400 --> 00:37:21.600
being equal to Newtonian
gravitational potential.

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:24.070
What this is showing is
that the geodesic equation,

00:37:24.070 --> 00:37:26.220
this equation that
describes a trajectory that

00:37:26.220 --> 00:37:30.060
is as straight as possible in
space time when it is given

00:37:30.060 --> 00:37:32.040
that particular
space time, it does

00:37:32.040 --> 00:37:35.960
give you the Newtonian
equation of motion, OK?

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:36.551
Yeah?

00:37:36.551 --> 00:37:37.964
AUDIENCE: Is there
still supposed

00:37:37.964 --> 00:37:40.710
to be a factor of m on
the right-hand side?

