00:37:56.722 --> 00:37:58.680
I remember what it was,
I remember what it was.

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:00.210
There's an m squared here.

00:38:00.210 --> 00:38:01.620
Thank you, Alex.

00:38:01.620 --> 00:38:03.450
There was an m squared here.

00:38:03.450 --> 00:38:06.858
There was an m and
an m squared here.

00:38:06.858 --> 00:38:08.400
That's what I screwed
up, and I think

00:38:08.400 --> 00:38:10.110
I have that wrong in my
handwritten notes, which is

00:38:10.110 --> 00:38:11.480
probably why I messed that up.

00:38:11.480 --> 00:38:13.410
Yeah, so this
equation was correct.

00:38:13.410 --> 00:38:15.270
And this should have
been here like so.

00:38:15.270 --> 00:38:17.690
We'll clear this
out and get this.

00:38:17.690 --> 00:38:20.978
Yeah, so module of
that little bobble.

00:38:20.978 --> 00:38:22.770
I just want to show
you this is essentially

00:38:22.770 --> 00:38:24.390
the Newtonian limit.

00:38:24.390 --> 00:38:27.390
Just give you a little
look at where we go ahead,

00:38:27.390 --> 00:38:28.890
there are two ways
that we are going

00:38:28.890 --> 00:38:31.920
to derive the field equations
of general relativity.

00:38:31.920 --> 00:38:34.440
The first one
essentially boils down

00:38:34.440 --> 00:38:38.610
to looking for certain tensors
that have the right symmetries

00:38:38.610 --> 00:38:42.270
and allow us to have
sort of a quantity that

00:38:42.270 --> 00:38:45.390
looks like derivatives on
the field equaling the stress

00:38:45.390 --> 00:38:47.040
energy tensor as the source.

00:38:47.040 --> 00:38:51.310
That only works up to
an overall constant,

00:38:51.310 --> 00:38:54.030
and this is actually the
way that Einstein originally

00:38:54.030 --> 00:38:57.450
developed the field equations,
was worked out all this stuff,

00:38:57.450 --> 00:39:00.390
and then by insisting that the
solution that emerge from this

00:39:00.390 --> 00:39:02.037
reproduced the
Newtonian equation

00:39:02.037 --> 00:39:03.870
and the Newtonian motion,
he was able to fix

00:39:03.870 --> 00:39:06.675
what that constant actually is.

00:39:06.675 --> 00:39:08.550
There's a more sophisticated
way of doing it,

00:39:08.550 --> 00:39:10.820
which I'm going to
also go through.

00:39:10.820 --> 00:39:13.260
But it's worth noting that is
the way Einstein originally

00:39:13.260 --> 00:39:14.550
did it.

00:39:14.550 --> 00:39:18.040
I had the privilege a
couple of years ago--

00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:20.680
I was at a conference
in Jerusalem,

00:39:20.680 --> 00:39:24.120
where the Einstein Papers
archive is located.

00:39:24.120 --> 00:39:27.080
And the guy who is the
main curator of this

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:28.830
was allowing those of
us at the conference

00:39:28.830 --> 00:39:29.910
to look through them.

00:39:29.910 --> 00:39:31.753
And I actually found--

00:39:31.753 --> 00:39:33.420
they had not yet quite
categorized that,

00:39:33.420 --> 00:39:36.200
but it was the papers very
much related to working

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:37.450
with these peculiar equations.

00:39:37.450 --> 00:39:39.575
I don't think he was trying
to fix the coefficient,

00:39:39.575 --> 00:39:43.860
but this spacetime can also be
used to compute the perihelion

00:39:43.860 --> 00:39:46.387
precession of mercury.

00:39:46.387 --> 00:39:48.720
And so it actually showed
Einstein working through that.

00:39:48.720 --> 00:39:53.230
And the thing which is really
cool was he screwed up a lot.

00:39:53.230 --> 00:39:55.570
The page that I was looking
at was full of errors.

00:39:55.570 --> 00:39:56.880
It would say things like--

00:39:56.880 --> 00:39:58.680
big things crossed out
and then "Nein nein nein!"

00:39:58.680 --> 00:39:59.520
written on the side.

00:39:59.520 --> 00:40:03.670
And so it made me feel
better about myself.

00:40:03.670 --> 00:40:05.383
All right.

00:40:05.383 --> 00:40:07.050
So everything that
we have done so far--

00:40:07.050 --> 00:40:10.950
we've been dancing
around this notion

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:12.708
of what is called "curvature."

00:40:16.700 --> 00:40:19.280
So I have used this
word several times,

00:40:19.280 --> 00:40:21.530
but I haven't made
this precise yet.

00:40:21.530 --> 00:40:24.170
Curvature is going to
be the precise idea

00:40:24.170 --> 00:40:28.540
of how two initially
parallel trajectories

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:29.450
cease to be parallel.

00:40:53.950 --> 00:40:59.650
So there's a couple of ways
that we can quantify this.

00:40:59.650 --> 00:41:01.990
The one which I
am going to use is

00:41:01.990 --> 00:41:06.280
one that's amendable
to, with relative ease,

00:41:06.280 --> 00:41:10.960
developing a particularly
important tensor, which

00:41:10.960 --> 00:41:12.910
characterizes curvature.

00:41:12.910 --> 00:41:14.650
And so what we're
going to do is look

00:41:14.650 --> 00:41:17.950
at the behavior of a
vector that is parallel

00:41:17.950 --> 00:41:26.310
transported in a
non-infinitesimal region

00:41:26.310 --> 00:41:27.185
of a curved manifold.

00:41:46.330 --> 00:41:47.890
So for the purpose
of this sketch,

00:41:47.890 --> 00:41:50.710
I'm going to make this
closed figure be a triangle.

00:41:50.710 --> 00:41:52.120
When I actually do the
calculation in just a moment,

00:41:52.120 --> 00:41:53.830
I'm going to use a
little parallelogram.

00:41:53.830 --> 00:41:59.940
So around a closed figure,
I want a curved manifold.

00:42:07.320 --> 00:42:09.300
So suppose my
curvature's actually 0,

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:20.990
and I do this for a triangle
that is on the blackboard.

00:42:20.990 --> 00:42:26.258
So let's say I start out with a
vector that points from A to B.

00:42:26.258 --> 00:42:28.550
And what I'm going to do is
just parallel transport it.

00:42:28.550 --> 00:42:32.190
And in the case, goes, doo, doo,
doo, doo, doo, doo, doo, doo,

00:42:32.190 --> 00:42:35.452
doo, doo, doo, doo.

00:42:35.452 --> 00:42:37.160
This is an experiment
you can do at home.

00:42:37.160 --> 00:42:39.620
When it comes back,
it's pointing exactly

00:42:39.620 --> 00:42:41.098
the way it was initially.

00:42:57.710 --> 00:43:02.510
Let me also just note
that this triangle--

00:43:02.510 --> 00:43:07.820
the sum of its internal
angles is 180 degrees.

00:43:14.033 --> 00:43:15.200
Hopefully you all know that.

00:43:18.810 --> 00:43:21.750
Now, the next one--

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:24.520
if I'd had a little
bit more time,

00:43:24.520 --> 00:43:28.710
I would have grabbed one
of my daughter's balls

00:43:28.710 --> 00:43:30.000
to demonstrate this.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:31.708
But hopefully, if you
guys have something

00:43:31.708 --> 00:43:34.890
like a soccer ball
or a basketball,

00:43:34.890 --> 00:43:38.310
this is a little experiment
you can do by yourself.

00:43:38.310 --> 00:43:44.505
Now imagine a triangle
that is embedded

00:43:44.505 --> 00:43:45.630
on the surface of a sphere.

00:43:51.810 --> 00:43:56.940
So let's say this is the
North Pole of my sphere.

00:43:59.750 --> 00:44:00.605
Here's the equator.

00:44:03.730 --> 00:44:06.540
So what I'm going
to imagine is--

00:44:06.540 --> 00:44:08.100
let's say I start up here.

00:44:08.100 --> 00:44:11.035
Let's make the North
Pole be point A.

00:44:11.035 --> 00:44:14.610
I move on a trajectory
that is as straight as I

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:15.510
am allowed to be.

00:44:15.510 --> 00:44:18.030
And remember, if I'm a
one-dimensional being living

00:44:18.030 --> 00:44:20.490
on the surface of this thing,
that's a straight line.

00:44:20.490 --> 00:44:22.885
It only looks straight
looks curved to us

00:44:22.885 --> 00:44:25.260
because we see a third dimension
that this whole thing is

00:44:25.260 --> 00:44:26.873
embedded in.

00:44:26.873 --> 00:44:28.290
And this thing's
going to come in,

00:44:28.290 --> 00:44:31.680
and it actually hits the
equator at a right angle, OK?

00:44:31.680 --> 00:44:33.360
No ifs, ands, or buts about it.

00:44:33.360 --> 00:44:35.790
It's a bloody right angle.

00:44:35.790 --> 00:44:36.930
And then I'm going to--

00:44:36.930 --> 00:44:38.970
let's call this point B--

00:44:38.970 --> 00:44:41.640
walk back along the
equator here till I

00:44:41.640 --> 00:44:45.200
reach a point which
I will call C.

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:48.680
And then I'm going to go
straight north until I

00:44:48.680 --> 00:44:52.450
come back up to the North Pole.

00:44:55.780 --> 00:44:59.590
This is a triangle in which all
three angles are 90 degrees.

00:45:11.080 --> 00:45:12.690
So here is a great
little experiment

00:45:12.690 --> 00:45:15.127
that's very easy for
you to do at home.

00:45:15.127 --> 00:45:16.960
Does anyone happen to
have a ball with them?

00:45:16.960 --> 00:45:17.640
OK, never mind.

00:45:22.340 --> 00:45:24.090
Let me look at my notes
for just a second.

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:33.205
So let's say I start
out here at point A,

00:45:33.205 --> 00:45:37.610
and I have my vector pointing
in the south direction.

00:45:37.610 --> 00:45:43.305
So this guy goes down here.

00:45:43.305 --> 00:45:45.430
And what you'll see is it
goes down to the equator,

00:45:45.430 --> 00:45:47.390
and it keeps pointing south.

00:45:47.390 --> 00:45:55.260
Then I bring it along over here,
bring it back up to the north.

00:45:55.260 --> 00:45:58.000
The vector has been
rotated by 90 degrees

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:00.680
as it goes around that pass.

00:46:00.680 --> 00:46:03.112
It's a really,
fun, exciting demo.

00:46:03.112 --> 00:46:05.570
If you've got a ball at home,
you can do this over and over

00:46:05.570 --> 00:46:06.070
again.

00:46:06.070 --> 00:46:07.888
It's endless fun.

00:46:07.888 --> 00:46:10.430
I'm being slightly silly here,
but there's an important point

00:46:10.430 --> 00:46:11.300
to be made.

00:46:11.300 --> 00:46:21.110
When you do this operation,
parallel transport

00:46:21.110 --> 00:46:22.160
rotates the vector.

00:46:25.410 --> 00:46:27.960
It turns out that, if you are
working on a two-dimensional

00:46:27.960 --> 00:46:30.720
manifold-- particularly, I think
it's a two-dimensional manifold

00:46:30.720 --> 00:46:31.763
that is--

00:46:31.763 --> 00:46:33.180
it may have to be
of what's called

00:46:33.180 --> 00:46:34.680
constant curvature--
in other words,

00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:38.450
either a surface, a
plane, or a hyperbola.

00:46:42.190 --> 00:46:52.480
It actually rotates by
an angle of whatever

00:46:52.480 --> 00:46:58.360
is internal angle of the
triangle minus 180 degrees.

00:46:58.360 --> 00:47:01.108
So in this case, it would
rotate it by 90 degrees.

00:47:01.108 --> 00:47:03.150
If you took this thing
and you actually opened it

00:47:03.150 --> 00:47:05.392
up all the way, you
could basically, just

00:47:05.392 --> 00:47:07.600
by taking this leg and making
it as long as you want,

00:47:07.600 --> 00:47:08.580
you can make it to 0.

00:47:08.580 --> 00:47:11.590
You can make it huge.

00:47:11.590 --> 00:47:14.430
And when you do so, you'll just
rotate that vector all the more

00:47:14.430 --> 00:47:15.180
as it goes around.

00:47:18.120 --> 00:47:24.170
This operation, by the
way, is called a holonomy.

00:47:24.170 --> 00:47:27.120
I throw that out there
because, last time I looked,

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:28.710
there was a decent
Wikipedia page

00:47:28.710 --> 00:47:32.900
on this that has some cool
animated graphics on it.

00:47:42.550 --> 00:47:45.340
Also, MathWorld.Wolfram.com
had some good stuff.

00:47:52.920 --> 00:47:54.900
So this has good
descriptions that you

00:47:54.900 --> 00:47:57.900
can find it all on Google.

00:47:57.900 --> 00:47:59.350
All right.

00:47:59.350 --> 00:48:02.340
What I want to do is take
some of these somewhat vague

00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:02.980
notions--

00:48:02.980 --> 00:48:04.980
so hopefully, I made
it intuitively clear

00:48:04.980 --> 00:48:06.180
that there's something
very interesting that

00:48:06.180 --> 00:48:07.590
happens when I
parallel transport

00:48:07.590 --> 00:48:11.580
a vector around these figures,
depending upon the underlying

00:48:11.580 --> 00:48:14.350
geometry of the manifold
that they're embedded in.

00:48:14.350 --> 00:48:16.137
Let's try to make
it more precise now.

00:48:16.137 --> 00:48:17.970
And I'm going to start
all the way over here

00:48:17.970 --> 00:48:20.800
because I'm going to want big,
clean boards to illustrate

00:48:20.800 --> 00:48:21.300
this.

00:48:33.130 --> 00:48:33.630
OK.

00:48:33.630 --> 00:48:38.790
So suppose I'm in some
coordinate system,

00:48:38.790 --> 00:48:44.160
and this line I've written here
represents a line of constant.

00:48:44.160 --> 00:48:48.708
So lambda is one
particular member

00:48:48.708 --> 00:48:50.250
of your set of
spacetime coordinates,

00:48:50.250 --> 00:48:52.885
so it might be time
or radius or maybe

00:48:52.885 --> 00:48:54.510
you work in some
crazy querying system.

00:48:54.510 --> 00:48:57.270
But lambda is meant to
represent some particular member

00:48:57.270 --> 00:49:00.180
of your coordinate system.

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:04.580
And then there's another track
over here, which is displaced

00:49:04.580 --> 00:49:10.160
from it by delta x lambda, OK?

00:49:10.160 --> 00:49:12.380
So everywhere along here,
one of your coordinates

00:49:12.380 --> 00:49:14.323
is equal to the value, x lambda.

00:49:14.323 --> 00:49:16.490
Everywhere along here wanted,
that same coordinate's

00:49:16.490 --> 00:49:18.350
equal to x lambda
plus dx lambda.

00:49:21.720 --> 00:49:26.350
Along this trajectory,
there's a different coordinate

00:49:26.350 --> 00:49:27.820
that is kept constant.

00:49:27.820 --> 00:49:29.330
Lambda and sigma
are not the same.

00:49:29.330 --> 00:49:31.480
So there is some
coordinate whose value

00:49:31.480 --> 00:49:35.190
I will label as sigma that
is constant along there.

00:49:35.190 --> 00:49:40.050
And along this one,
it is also constant.

00:49:43.080 --> 00:49:57.290
Let me label the four
vertices, A, B, C, and D.

00:49:57.290 --> 00:50:00.590
And let me number
these four edges--

00:50:00.590 --> 00:50:08.190
one, two, three, and four.

00:50:08.190 --> 00:50:11.460
What I am going to
imagine doing is parallel

00:50:11.460 --> 00:50:15.180
transporting some vector,
v alpha, around this loop.

00:50:27.772 --> 00:50:29.230
So what I'm going
to do is generate

00:50:29.230 --> 00:50:33.170
the equations that describe
how it changes as a transport.

00:50:33.170 --> 00:50:35.770
I'm going to start at A, so
v is pointing along here.

00:50:35.770 --> 00:50:51.680
Transport it to B to C
to D and then back to A.

00:50:51.680 --> 00:50:54.250
So let me very carefully
do the first leg.

00:50:54.250 --> 00:50:56.547
Once you get the
pattern, the others

00:50:56.547 --> 00:50:58.130
can be done a little
bit more quickly.

00:51:04.500 --> 00:51:07.640
So the coordinate-- let's see.

00:51:07.640 --> 00:51:09.400
Hang on just one moment.

00:51:09.400 --> 00:51:12.065
Yeah, so I am going
from A to B first.

00:51:16.090 --> 00:51:20.920
So as I move from A to B,
x lambda remains constant,

00:51:20.920 --> 00:51:23.810
and the coordinate x
sigma is increasing.

00:51:23.810 --> 00:51:26.470
So I am moving in a
direction that points

00:51:26.470 --> 00:51:30.265
along the unit vector associated
with the sigma coordinate.

00:51:39.190 --> 00:51:42.373
So I'm going to say that
there's a basis vector.

00:51:42.373 --> 00:51:43.790
I shouldn't have
said unit vector.

00:51:43.790 --> 00:51:46.090
I don't know its magnitude.

00:51:46.090 --> 00:51:48.080
I'm pointing along
the direction in which

00:51:48.080 --> 00:51:50.490
coordinate sigma is increasing.

00:51:50.490 --> 00:51:53.120
And so parallel
transporting this vector

00:51:53.120 --> 00:52:00.070
amounts to requiring that
my covariant derivative

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:05.890
along the sigma
basis vector is 0.

00:52:09.690 --> 00:52:10.890
This can be written out.

00:52:10.890 --> 00:52:15.100
Turn this into index form.

00:52:23.828 --> 00:52:24.620
It looks like this.

00:52:41.500 --> 00:52:43.560
OK, no surprises.

00:52:43.560 --> 00:52:45.560
So now what I'm going
to do is, essentially,

00:52:45.560 --> 00:52:48.650
I'm going to write down an
integral that would describe

00:52:48.650 --> 00:53:20.510
how v alpha changes as I move
from A to B. When I do this,

00:53:20.510 --> 00:53:24.040
I will then get the value
of the vector at point B.

00:53:24.040 --> 00:53:28.990
So the way I'm going to
write this is v alpha at B

00:53:28.990 --> 00:53:33.670
is equal to v alpha, the
initial value of this thing,

00:53:33.670 --> 00:53:38.410
minus what I get when I
integrate along leg one--

00:53:38.410 --> 00:53:47.390
gamma alpha sigma
mu phi mu dx sigma.

00:53:47.390 --> 00:53:49.140
Everyone happy with that?

00:53:49.140 --> 00:53:52.480
So everything I've done
over here, so far, I think,

00:53:52.480 --> 00:53:53.740
is probably just fine.

00:53:53.740 --> 00:53:56.000
When you've got a differential
equation, integrate it.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:56.500
Boom.

00:53:56.500 --> 00:53:57.208
You integrate it.

00:53:57.208 --> 00:53:58.166
You got your new thing.

00:53:58.166 --> 00:54:00.041
We're going to actually
solve these integrals

00:54:00.041 --> 00:54:02.890
in a few moments, but we'll
just leave it like this for now.

00:54:02.890 --> 00:54:04.420
So that's the first step.

00:54:04.420 --> 00:54:07.050
I got a couple more to
do, but hopefully you

00:54:07.050 --> 00:54:08.050
can now see the pattern.

00:54:13.680 --> 00:54:18.180
If I go from B to
C, I am now moving

00:54:18.180 --> 00:54:24.350
in the direction
of lambda, and I'm

00:54:24.350 --> 00:54:26.970
holding the value of that
