01:09:26.590 --> 01:09:33.960
And what I finally get is that
the change in the vector v

01:09:33.960 --> 01:09:42.260
transported along a loop
whose sides are delta x lambda

01:09:42.260 --> 01:09:44.990
and delta sigma--

01:09:44.990 --> 01:09:48.220
it's a quantity that is linear
in those two displacements.

01:09:48.220 --> 01:09:58.590
It's linear in the vector and
involves this four index tensor

01:09:58.590 --> 01:10:15.930
whose value depends on
derivatives of the connection

01:10:15.930 --> 01:10:21.873
and two nonlinear terms
in the connection.

01:10:40.620 --> 01:10:48.810
This quantity is a mathematical
entity known as the Riemann

01:10:48.810 --> 01:10:49.680
curvature tensor.

01:11:04.200 --> 01:11:07.170
Even though it involves
connection coefficients,

01:11:07.170 --> 01:11:09.030
Christoffel symbols,
and we argued before--

01:11:09.030 --> 01:11:10.890
and you guys did a homework
exercise where you show this--

01:11:10.890 --> 01:11:12.540
that the connection,
the Christoffel,

01:11:12.540 --> 01:11:16.500
is not tensorial, this
combination of them,

01:11:16.500 --> 01:11:20.550
basically that the terms come
together in such a way that,

01:11:20.550 --> 01:11:22.290
when you change
your representation,

01:11:22.290 --> 01:11:24.750
the nontensorial bits
cancel each other out

01:11:24.750 --> 01:11:27.520
from the terms that are being
subtracted against one another.

01:11:27.520 --> 01:11:29.250
So this is, indeed,
a true tensor.

01:11:37.525 --> 01:11:38.900
There's an equivalent
definition,

01:11:38.900 --> 01:11:40.067
if you are reading Carroll--

01:11:42.390 --> 01:11:43.980
so essentially,
what I just walked

01:11:43.980 --> 01:11:47.340
through here is an
integral equivalent

01:11:47.340 --> 01:11:50.490
of the following
commutator being applied

01:11:50.490 --> 01:11:55.890
to the vector v.
Some textbooks simply

01:11:55.890 --> 01:12:00.430
state the Riemann
tensor is related

01:12:00.430 --> 01:12:03.610
to the commutator of
partial derivatives acting

01:12:03.610 --> 01:12:09.812
upon a four-vector like so.

01:12:09.812 --> 01:12:12.270
With a little bit of effort,
you can show that what this is

01:12:12.270 --> 01:12:15.172
is, essentially, a way of--

01:12:15.172 --> 01:12:17.130
what I worked out over
there is a geometric way

01:12:17.130 --> 01:12:20.310
of understanding what
that commutator means.

01:12:20.310 --> 01:12:23.640
Incidentally, one thing, which
I think is worth calling out--

01:12:28.160 --> 01:12:32.630
when you apply
this to a one-form

01:12:32.630 --> 01:12:42.040
or a downstairs component, you
get this with a minus sign.

01:12:42.040 --> 01:12:44.860
If you are reading the
textbook by Schutz,

01:12:44.860 --> 01:12:47.530
Schutz has this sign wrong
in its first edition.

01:12:54.580 --> 01:12:56.950
Hopefully all copies
of the first edition

01:12:56.950 --> 01:13:00.040
are rare enough now that, if
you are looking at Schutz--

01:13:00.040 --> 01:13:01.870
Schutz it's actually
a wonderful textbook

01:13:01.870 --> 01:13:04.492
for an early introduction
to this field,

01:13:04.492 --> 01:13:06.700
but if you happen to get a
hold of the first edition,

01:13:06.700 --> 01:13:07.950
just be aware that there is--

01:13:07.950 --> 01:13:10.370
I think it's on page
171 of the textbook,

01:13:10.370 --> 01:13:12.940
you'll see this written.

01:13:12.940 --> 01:13:14.650
So I've actually
written a couple papers

01:13:14.650 --> 01:13:17.102
with Bernard Schutz, and so
I'm allowed to tease him.

01:13:17.102 --> 01:13:18.310
Not only did he get it wrong.

01:13:18.310 --> 01:13:19.990
He actually came up with
an intuitive argument

01:13:19.990 --> 01:13:20.575
that is wrong.

01:13:22.818 --> 01:13:25.360
Sometimes you just need to sit
down and bloody well calculate

01:13:25.360 --> 01:13:27.400
something because you
can almost always come up

01:13:27.400 --> 01:13:30.113
with an argument to convince you
of something that's not true.

01:13:30.113 --> 01:13:32.530
And I'm afraid that's what he
did in this particular case.

01:13:35.045 --> 01:13:37.420
So I have a couple notes in
there about what is sometimes

01:13:37.420 --> 01:13:40.750
called curvature coupling,
which essentially tells us--

01:13:40.750 --> 01:13:42.650
I pointed out in
the last lecture

01:13:42.650 --> 01:13:44.410
that when we're
dealing with geodesics,

01:13:44.410 --> 01:13:48.700
strictly speaking they describe,
completely point-like, almost

01:13:48.700 --> 01:13:52.090
just a monopole and no structure
and no shape whatsoever moving

01:13:52.090 --> 01:13:53.710
through spacetime.

01:13:53.710 --> 01:13:56.080
If you have a larger
body or a body that

01:13:56.080 --> 01:13:58.550
has any kind of multipolar
structure associated with it,

01:13:58.550 --> 01:13:59.300
those multipoles--

01:13:59.300 --> 01:14:01.675
you can think of that additional
structure is essentially

01:14:01.675 --> 01:14:03.250
filling up part of
the local Lorentz

01:14:03.250 --> 01:14:06.820
frame around the center
of mass of that point,

01:14:06.820 --> 01:14:10.840
and they couple the
spacetime and push it away

01:14:10.840 --> 01:14:12.220
from the geodesic.

01:14:12.220 --> 01:14:14.380
This Riemann tensor
actually describes the way

01:14:14.380 --> 01:14:17.200
in which that body couples
to the background spacetime,

01:14:17.200 --> 01:14:19.360
that it might be falling in.

01:14:19.360 --> 01:14:21.590
So this ends up playing
a really important role.

01:14:21.590 --> 01:14:25.330
For instance, when you study
the precession of equinoxes,

01:14:25.330 --> 01:14:27.992
we learn how to do this
Newtonian theory using

01:14:27.992 --> 01:14:29.950
the action of tides from
the Earth and the moon

01:14:29.950 --> 01:14:31.480
on a planet like the Earth.

01:14:31.480 --> 01:14:32.980
This ends up being
the quantity that

01:14:32.980 --> 01:14:35.750
mathematically encapsulates
tides and general relativity.

01:14:35.750 --> 01:14:37.790
So it enters into there.

01:14:37.790 --> 01:14:41.720
So I'm going to sketch
through this very,

01:14:41.720 --> 01:14:45.700
very quickly, simply because
we don't have a lot of time,

01:14:45.700 --> 01:14:48.910
and there's good discussion of
this in various other places.

01:14:48.910 --> 01:14:51.462
But let me just point out that--

01:14:51.462 --> 01:14:52.420
you look at this thing.

01:14:52.420 --> 01:14:56.410
It's a four-index
tensor, and each index

01:14:56.410 --> 01:14:57.355
can take four values.

01:15:04.550 --> 01:15:09.410
That makes it look like
it has 256 components.

