01:15:42.650 --> 01:15:43.400
and you know what?

01:15:43.400 --> 01:15:53.620
Let me write it
out in n dimensions

01:15:53.620 --> 01:15:59.350
from n to the 4, which is what
you'd expect for a four index

01:15:59.350 --> 01:16:06.100
object in n
dimensions, down to n

01:16:06.100 --> 01:16:12.330
squared times m squared
minus 1 over 12th.

01:16:12.330 --> 01:16:13.705
So where I want
to conclude today

01:16:13.705 --> 01:16:15.360
is let's just take
a look at what that

01:16:15.360 --> 01:16:17.730
turns into for a couple
of different numbers

01:16:17.730 --> 01:16:18.794
and dimensions.

01:16:30.170 --> 01:16:33.650
So if you do n
equals 1, you get 0.

01:16:33.650 --> 01:16:36.030
So the Riemann tensor
has no components

01:16:36.030 --> 01:16:37.655
on a one-dimensional manifold.

01:16:37.655 --> 01:16:39.030
There's a simple
reason for that.

01:16:39.030 --> 01:16:40.488
Remember the way
we defined it, OK?

01:16:40.488 --> 01:16:42.480
We did this by
parallel transporting

01:16:42.480 --> 01:16:44.160
around a particular figure.

01:16:44.160 --> 01:16:47.860
If you're in one dimension,
this is all you can do.

01:16:47.860 --> 01:16:50.280
There's no holonomy
operation in one dimension.

01:16:50.280 --> 01:16:52.050
You can't do that.

01:16:52.050 --> 01:16:55.830
So no curvature.

01:16:55.830 --> 01:16:58.228
If you want to be a real
pedant and someone says,

01:16:58.228 --> 01:17:00.020
well, look at a curved
line, you'll go, ah,

01:17:00.020 --> 01:17:01.103
but lines can't be curved.

01:17:04.060 --> 01:17:06.120
n equals 2.

01:17:06.120 --> 01:17:09.950
So you get 2 squared, 2
squared minus 1 over 12--

01:17:09.950 --> 01:17:12.410
you get 1.

01:17:12.410 --> 01:17:15.380
So if you're working
in two dimensions,

01:17:15.380 --> 01:17:17.600
there is a single number
that characterizes

01:17:17.600 --> 01:17:22.370
the curvature at every
point, and this is often

01:17:22.370 --> 01:17:28.430
thought of as just a
radius of curvature.

01:17:28.430 --> 01:17:30.620
Simplest example is
if you have a sphere.

01:17:30.620 --> 01:17:34.040
Sphere is completely
characterized by its radius.

01:17:34.040 --> 01:17:39.290
But if you imagine that it's
like a sphere that you squash,

01:17:39.290 --> 01:17:41.570
well, you can imagine
at every point

01:17:41.570 --> 01:17:43.340
that there is a
particular sphere that

01:17:43.340 --> 01:17:45.590
is tangent to that
point, and the radius

01:17:45.590 --> 01:17:48.620
of curvature of
the tangent sphere

01:17:48.620 --> 01:17:52.057
is the one that defines the
curvature at that point.

01:17:52.057 --> 01:17:54.640
I'm going to skip three because
it's not all that interesting.

01:17:54.640 --> 01:17:58.330
The one that is more important
is, if you do n equals 4,

01:17:58.330 --> 01:18:06.220
you'll wind up with 16 times
15 over 12, which is 20.

01:18:06.220 --> 01:18:11.410
This is exactly the
number of derivatives

01:18:11.410 --> 01:18:14.230
that we could not
cancel out when

01:18:14.230 --> 01:18:18.010
we did the exercise a couple
of lectures ago of assessing

01:18:18.010 --> 01:18:23.530
how well we can make spacetime
have a flat representation

01:18:23.530 --> 01:18:24.910
in the vicinity of some point.

01:18:34.070 --> 01:18:43.150
It's the number of leftover
constraints at second order

01:18:43.150 --> 01:18:44.410
in a freely falling frame.

01:18:53.320 --> 01:18:55.690
All right so I'm going
to stop there for today.

01:18:55.690 --> 01:18:57.465
That's a nice place
for us to stop.

01:19:00.720 --> 01:19:02.390
Keep watching your emails.

01:19:02.390 --> 01:19:04.470
We're in an
interesting situation.

01:19:04.470 --> 01:19:07.950
Life at MIT is evolving.

01:19:07.950 --> 01:19:10.380
But when we pick it up
in one form or another,

01:19:10.380 --> 01:19:13.230
what I'm going to do first
is talk a little bit more

01:19:13.230 --> 01:19:14.640
about the symmetry
of this object

01:19:14.640 --> 01:19:17.460
because there's a couple
of explicit symmetries

01:19:17.460 --> 01:19:20.330
that lead to that reduction
from n to the 4th to n squared

01:19:20.330 --> 01:19:22.800
n squared minus 1 over
12, and it's useful for us

01:19:22.800 --> 01:19:25.350
to go through them and
see what they look like.

01:19:25.350 --> 01:19:27.900
And then I also want to talk
about a couple of variants

01:19:27.900 --> 01:19:29.520
on this curvature tensor, OK?

01:19:29.520 --> 01:19:31.920
So just to give you a
little bit of a preview--

01:19:31.920 --> 01:19:36.270
the curvature tensor--
it's a four index object.

01:19:36.270 --> 01:19:44.165
We have argued
already that we're

01:19:44.165 --> 01:19:45.540
going to end up
doing things that

01:19:45.540 --> 01:19:47.880
look like looking at
derivatives of the metric

01:19:47.880 --> 01:19:49.440
being equal to our source.

01:19:49.440 --> 01:19:52.560
Our source is a two-index
object, the stress energy

01:19:52.560 --> 01:19:53.770
tensor.

01:19:53.770 --> 01:19:55.687
We've got gotta get
rid of two indices.

01:19:55.687 --> 01:19:57.270
And so what we're
going to do is we're

01:19:57.270 --> 01:20:00.570
going to essentially contract
this guy with a couple

01:20:00.570 --> 01:20:04.080
of powers of the metric
in order to trace over

01:20:04.080 --> 01:20:08.070
certain combinations of indices
and make two index variants

01:20:08.070 --> 01:20:09.683
of the curvature tensor.

01:20:09.683 --> 01:20:11.850
And we're also going to
look at derivatives of this,

01:20:11.850 --> 01:20:14.520
because it turns out that there
is a particular combination

01:20:14.520 --> 01:20:16.020
of derivatives at
the Riemann tensor

01:20:16.020 --> 01:20:18.182
that has an important
geometrical meaning.

01:20:18.182 --> 01:20:20.640
What we're going to find is
that, when we combine these two

01:20:20.640 --> 01:20:24.660
notions, there is a
particular divergence

01:20:24.660 --> 01:20:28.503
of a particular variant of the
curvature tensor that is 0.

01:20:28.503 --> 01:20:30.420
In other words, we can
make a curvature tensor

01:20:30.420 --> 01:20:32.490
that is divergence-free.

01:20:32.490 --> 01:20:36.300
Our stress energy tensor
is divergence-free.

01:20:36.300 --> 01:20:38.910
I wonder if one is
related to the other.

01:20:38.910 --> 01:20:40.935
That, in a nutshell,
is how Einstein came up

01:20:40.935 --> 01:20:43.080
with general relativity,
by asking that question

01:20:43.080 --> 01:20:45.840
and then just seeing
what happened.

01:20:45.840 --> 01:20:48.350
So that's what we're
going to go through next.